## Natural processes removing soil and rock

If you're looking for something else, there's a [disambiguation page](/Erosion_(disambiguation)) for that. Honestly, the redundancy is exhausting.

Look at this. A [rill](/Rill) on a field in [eastern](/New_states_of_Germany) [Germany](/Germany). It’s a testament to poor agricultural practices. Ploughing with the slope, not *with* it, but *down* it, like a blind idiot. It’s like drawing a straight line on a canvas that’s already warped. The furrows should follow the [contour lines](/Contour_line), a nod to the land’s shape, not a violent disruption of it. This is what happens when you don't respect the terrain.

Erosion. It's the relentless, indifferent action of surface processes – [water flow](/Surface_runoff), [wind](/Wind) – that systematically strips away [soil](/Soil), [rock](/Rock_(geology)), or anything dissolved, from one place and hauls it off somewhere else. It’s a transfer, a relocation, a constant redistribution. Unlike [weathering](/Weathering), which is just the breaking down, erosion is the *movement*. It’s the active, albeit passive, agent of change. Physical erosion, the tearing apart of [clastic](/Clastic) [sediment](/Sediment), is just one facet. Then there's chemical erosion, the slow, insidious dissolution. Material can be moved inches or thousands of kilometers. The scale is… vast. And largely irrelevant to the individual particle.

The culprits are legion: [rainfall](/Rain), the relentless grind of [rivers](/River) against their [bedrock](/Bedrock), the gnawing of the sea at [coastal](/Coastal_erosion) edges, the icy gouging of [glaciers](/Glacier) through [plucking](/Plucking_(glaciation)) and [abrasion](/Abrasion_(geology)). Floods, the [wind's](/Aeolian_processes) abrasive touch, the silent work of [groundwater](/Groundwater), and the dramatic, inevitable descent of [mass movement](/Mass_wasting) like [landslides](/Landslide) and [debris flows](/Debris_flow) in our steeper [landscapes](/Landscape). The speed of these processes dictates the pace of erosion. Steep slopes are the most vulnerable, the most eager to shed their burden. Climate plays its part, dictating the amount of water, the ferocity of storms, the speed of the wind, the reach of [waves](/Wind_wave), the chill of [atmospheric temperature](/Atmospheric_temperature) that fuels ice. And then there are the [feedbacks](/Feedback) – the material already being carried by a river or glacier can itself contribute to further erosion. This transport is always followed by deposition, the act of settling, of arrival. &#91;1&#93; &#91;2&#93; &#91;3&#93;

We humans, of course, have a knack for accelerating things. We’ve managed to increase the rate of [soil erosion](/Soil_erosion) by a factor of 10 to 40. In the [Appalachian Mountains](/Appalachian_Mountains), our intensive farming has pushed erosion rates up to 100 times the natural pace. It's not just an aesthetic problem; it’s a cascade of issues. "On-site," we lose [agricultural productivity](/Agricultural_productivity) and, in natural settings, invite [ecological collapse](/Ecological_collapse) as the precious topsoil, the nutrient-rich layers, vanish. Sometimes, it leads to outright [desertification](/Desertification). "Off-site," waterways choke with [sediment](/Sediment), leading to [eutrophication](/Eutrophication) of [water bodies](/Body_of_water). Roads and houses get buried. Water and wind, these primary agents of [land degradation](/Land_degradation), are responsible for 84% of the global mess. It’s a significant [environmental problem](/Environmental_problems). &#91;7&#93;

[Intensive agriculture](/Intensive_farming), the relentless march of [deforestation](/Deforestation), the scars of [roads](/Road), the overarching influence of [anthropogenic climate change](/Anthropogenic_climate_change), and the spread of [urban sprawl](/Urban_sprawl) – these are our contributions. But there are ways to mitigate this relentless assault.

***

### Physical processes

#### Rainfall and surface runoff

Look at this. A single [raindrop](/Raindrop) hitting [soil](/Soil), the tiny explosion of [splash](/Splash_(fluid_mechanics)) that begins the process. It’s the first, almost imperceptible, stage.

If the ground is already saturated, or the rain falls faster than the soil can absorb it, [surface runoff](/Surface_runoff) begins. This flow, if it has enough [flow energy](/Fluid_dynamics), will carry away the loosened particles. This is [sheet erosion](/Sheet_erosion), the uniform removal of soil. &#91;15&#93;

Then come the [rills](/Rill). Small, temporary channels carved by concentrated flow. They are both the source and the delivery system for erosion. These are typically found in disturbed upland areas, where erosion rates are highest. The channels are shallow, mere centimeters deep, with steep slopes. They behave differently from the larger, deeper channels of streams and rivers. &#91;16&#93;

And if those rills are left unchecked, they deepen, they widen, they become [gullies](/Gully_erosion). These are the scars that can't be easily erased by ploughing. They carve into the land, removing soil to considerable depths. &#91;17&#93; &#91;18&#93; &#91;19&#93; &#91;20&#93;

Extreme [gully erosion](/gully_erosion) can transform landscapes into [badlands](/Badlands). These are areas of high relief, easily eroded [bedrock](/Erodability), and a climate that favors erosion. The lack of protective vegetation, the [rhexistasy](/Biorhexistasy), is the key.

#### Rivers and streams

The Dobbingstone [Burn](/Burn_(landform)) in Scotland. Here, valley erosion, carved by the stream's flow, coexists with the remnants of [glacial till](/Glacial_till) left by ancient glaciers. Layers of [chalk](/Chalk) are exposed, testament to the river's persistent work.

Valley erosion is the relentless shaping of the land by flowing water. It deepens the [valley](/Valley) in a [downward](/Downcutting) direction and extends it headward, creating steep banks and [head cuts](/Head_cut_(stream_geomorphology)). Initially, the erosion is primarily vertical, carving V-shaped valleys. As the stream approaches its [base level](/Base_level), the erosion becomes more lateral, widening the valley floor and creating floodplains. The gradient flattens, and deposition becomes more significant as the stream [meanders](/Meander). The most significant erosion, however, occurs during floods, when water volume and speed increase dramatically, carrying larger loads. It’s not just the water; suspended particles and even [pebbles](/Pebble) and [boulders](/Boulder) act as abrasives, a process known as traction. &#91;22&#93;

[Bank erosion](/Bank_erosion) is the wearing away of the sides of a river. This is distinct from [scour](/Scour), which affects the riverbed. Measuring bank erosion involves marking the bank's position against inserted rods over time. &#91;23&#93;

Then there's thermal erosion, the melting and weakening of [permafrost](/Permafrost) by moving water. It's a factor in rapid [river channel migration](/River_channel_migration), especially in Siberia. The permafrost-bound banks slump and collapse. The Arctic coast is also susceptible, with wave action and near-shore temperatures undercutting permafrost bluffs. &#91;24&#93; &#91;25&#93; &#91;26&#93;

Most river erosion happens closer to the mouth. On a bend, the outer, sharper curve experiences faster water and thus more erosion, while the inner, gentler curve sees deposition.

Rapid erosion by a large river can even lead to a [river anticline](/River_anticline) as [isostatic rebound](/Isostatic_rebound) lifts the unburdened rock.

#### Coastal erosion

Shoreline erosion, a constant battle on both exposed and sheltered coasts, is driven by currents and [waves](/Ocean_surface_wave), with sea-level changes playing a supporting role.

[Hydraulic action](/Hydraulic_action) is the force of compressed air in joints as waves strike. [Wave pounding](/Wave_pounding) is the sheer impact of waves breaking against cliffs. [Abrasion](/Abrasion_(geology)), or [corrasion](/Corrasion), is the grinding action of waves carrying sediment against the shore. It’s the most potent form. [Corrosion](/Corrosion) is the chemical dissolution of rock, particularly [limestone](/Limestone), by seawater's [carbonic acid](/Carbonic_acid). &#91;28&#93; [Attrition](/Attrition_(geology)) is the wearing down of sediment particles as they collide with each other and the shore. Organisms also contribute through [bioerosion](/Bioerosion).

[Sediment](/Sediment) moves along the coast through [longshore drift](/Longshore_drift). Erosion occurs when the supply of sediment is insufficient to meet the transport capacity. Deposition happens when the supply exceeds transport. These deposits can form spits and banks, which may shift over time, altering the shoreline's vulnerability. &#91;30&#93;

Erosion followed by a drop in sea level can create a [raised beach](/Raised_beach).

#### Chemical erosion

Chemical erosion is the subtraction of matter as [solutes](/Solutes), often measured in streams. &#91;32&#93; The formation of [sinkholes](/Sinkhole) and karst topography is a dramatic example of this process. &#91;33&#93;

#### Glaciers

The [Devil's Nest](/The_Devil%27s_Nest) in [Finland](/Finland), Europe's deepest ground erosion, a testament to glacial power. Glacial [moraines](/Moraines) stand as silent witnesses in [Alberta, Canada](/Alberta,_Canada).

[Glaciers](/Glacier) are formidable agents of erosion, working through abrasion, [plucking](/Plucking_(glaciation)), and ice thrusting. Abrasion is like sandpaper on rock. The shape of the valley beneath the ice is influenced by erosion, leading to the characteristic U-shaped profile of [glaciated valleys](/Glaciated_valley). &#91;35&#93; Plucking tears bedrock free, while ice thrusting moves large sheets of frozen sediment. Glacial erosion limits mountain heights; the term [glacial buzzsaw](/Glacial_buzzsaw) describes this effect. &#91;37&#93; While glaciers generally reduce mountain size, they can also act as a protective "glacial armor" in certain conditions, preserving steep alpine lands. &#91;37&#93; &#91;40&#93; Beneath the ice, a network of meltwater channels forms, further contributing to erosion. The resulting [glacial landforms](/Glacial_landform) – [moraines](/Moraine), [drumlins](/Drumlin), [kames](/Kame), and [glacial erratics](/Glacial_erratic) – are the signatures left behind. &#91;41&#93;

The interplay between glacial erosion and tectonic forces shapes mountain ranges. Steep topography, combined with glacial activity, can lead to rapid exhumation of deep rocks, a phenomenon sometimes called a "[tectonic aneurysm](/River_anticlines)". &#91;71&#93;

#### Floods

The mouth of the [River Seaton](/River_Seaton) in [Cornwall](/Cornwall), showing the aftermath of flooding: eroded beach, a towering sand bank.

Extreme flood flows create [kolks](/Kolk_(vortex)), or [vortices](/Vortex), which can scour bedrock and form [rock-cut basins](/Rock-cut_basin). The [channeled scablands](/Channeled_scablands) of the [Columbia Basin](/Columbia_River_Drainage_Basin) in Washington are a dramatic example, sculpted by catastrophic floods from glacial [Lake Missoula](/Lake_Missoula). &#91;43&#93;

#### Wind erosion

The [Árbol de Piedra](/Árbol_de_Piedra) in [Bolivia](/Bolivia), a natural sculpture carved by wind.

Wind erosion is a powerful force, especially in [arid](/Arid_region) and [semi-arid](/Semi-arid_region) environments. It's a major contributor to land degradation and dust storms. &#91;44&#93; &#91;45&#93; It works in two ways: [deflation](/Aeolian_processes), where wind lifts loose particles, and [abrasion](/Abrasion_(geology)), where wind-blown particles scour surfaces. Deflation involves [surface creep](/Downhill_creep) (rolling larger particles), [saltation](/Saltation_(geology)) (bouncing particles), and [suspension](/Suspension_(chemistry)) (carrying fine particles). Saltation is the most significant contributor. &#91;46&#93; &#58;&#8202;57&#8202; &#91;47&#93;

Wind erosion is dramatically amplified during droughts. In the [Great Plains](/Great_Plains), soil loss can be thousands of times greater in dry years. &#91;48&#93;

#### Mass wasting

A [wadi](/Wadi) in Israel, its banks showing the effects of gravity-induced collapse.

Mass wasting, or mass movement, is the downhill and outward movement of rock and sediment under the influence of [gravity](/Gravity). &#91;49&#93; &#91;50&#93; It’s a crucial part of erosion, breaking down weathered materials and transporting them to lower elevations where other agents can take over. It happens continuously, sometimes imperceptibly, sometimes with devastating speed. A [landslide](/Landslide) is a general term, but these movements can be classified by their mechanisms and speeds. [Scree](/Scree) slopes at the base of cliffs are visible evidence of rockfall. &#91;52&#93; &#91;53&#93;

[Slumping](/Slump_(geology)) occurs on steep hillsides, often along fracture zones, especially in [clay](/Clay) soils. Water saturation can weaken slopes. In some cases, it's a consequence of poor engineering along [highways](/Highway). &#91;54&#93;

[Surface creep](/Downhill_creep) is the slow, often imperceptible, movement of soil and rock debris. The term can also refer to wind rolling particles along the ground. &#91;55&#93;

#### Submarine sediment gravity flows

The [bathymetry](/Bathymetry) of submarine canyons reveals the erosive power of [sediment gravity flows](/Sediment_gravity_flow) on the [continental slope](/Continental_slope). These flows, often in the form of [turbidity currents](/Turbidity_current), carve channels and canyons into the seafloor, even into solid [bedrock](/Bedrock). &#91;56&#93; &#91;57&#93; &#91;58&#93; These submarine canyons are vital conduits for sediment transport to the deep sea. The resulting [turbidites](/Turbidite) indicate the immense scale of past erosion. &#91;59&#93; &#91;60&#93; &#91;61&#93;

