### Erosion at various scales

#### Mountain ranges

It takes millions of years for [mountain ranges](/Mountain_range) to erode into near-oblivion. Estimates suggest it could take over 450 million years to reduce a mass like the [Himalaya](/Himalaya) to a peneplain, assuming no major [sea-level changes](/Sea_level). &#91;74&#93; Erosion can create patterns of similar summit heights, known as [summit accordance](/Summit_accordance). &#91;75&#93; Some argue that [extensional](/Extensional_tectonics) processes during [post-orogenic collapse](/Post-orogenic_collapse) are more effective at lowering mountain heights than erosion. &#91;76&#93;

The [Timanides](/Timanide_Orogen) in Northern Russia are an example of heavily eroded mountain ranges. Their erosion products are found in the [East European Platform](/East_European_Platform), with evidence suggesting erosion began in the Cambrian and intensified in the [Ordovician](/Ordovician). &#91;77&#93;

#### Soils

If erosion outpaces [soil formation](/Soil_formation), the soil is destroyed. &#91;78&#93; Even lower rates of erosion can prevent the development of mature [soil horizons](/Soil_horizon). [Inceptisols](/Inceptisol) might form on landscapes that, if stable, would develop into richer [Alfisols](/Alfisols). &#91;79&#93;

Human activities have amplified soil erosion rates globally by 10–40 times. This accelerated erosion leads to reduced [agricultural productivity](/Agricultural_productivity) and [ecological collapse](/Ecological_collapse) due to the loss of fertile topsoil. In severe cases, it results in [desertification](/Desertification). Off-site impacts include [sedimentation of waterways](/Sediment) and [eutrophication](/Eutrophication). Water and wind erosion are the primary drivers of [land degradation](/Land_degradation), responsible for about 84% of the global extent of such areas. &#91;10&#93; &#91;80&#93;

In the United States, farmers on [highly erodible land](/Highly_erodible_land) often must adhere to conservation plans to receive agricultural aid. &#91;81&#93;

